body:
Currently, we have the [`Default`](https://doc.rust-lang.org/core/default/trait.Default.html) trait that allows a type to construct a default instance of itself:

```rust
pub trait Default {
    fn default() -> Self;
}
```

I've been working on an object allocator crate, and I've found it very useful to have a similar trait that, instead of returning a value, initializes a value at a location in memory: `UnsafeDefault`:

```rust
pub unsafe trait UnsafeDefault {
    unsafe fn unsafe_default(ptr: *mut Self);
}
```

The contract is that `ptr` points to an uninitialized region of memory large enough to hold an instance of the type, and when `unsafe_default` has returned, that memory is initialized to a valid instance of the type. For example:

```rust
impl<T: UnsafeDefault> Default for T {
    fn default() -> T {
        unsafe {
            use core::mem::uninitialized;
            let mut t = uninitialized();
            Self::unsafe_default(&mut t);
            t
        }
    }
}
```

I've found `UnsafeDefault` to be a very useful primitive to have in implementing allocators - both for ergonomics and for performance. I think adding it to `core` and `std` could be very useful - especially as we try to clean up the story around custom allocators (which, in my experience, can benefit from using `UnsafeDefault` in their public APIs).
